The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, March 28, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 27: The mutual funds industry is set to see more mergers and acquisitions as it can not afford to have many small players, UTI Mutual Fund chairman M. Damodaran said here today. Consolidation in the mutual fund industry has to take place. We simply cannot afford to have so many small players, Damodaran said at a summit organised by Assocham and Amfi. 																								 Mumbai, March 27: The Reserve Bank offices and branches of agency banks in the city and satellite township of Navi Mumbai will remain open on March 30, a holiday on account of Ramnawmi, and March 31 to facilitate direct tax collection. Depending on the governments requirements and the rush for payment of taxes, the banking hours may be suitably extended and counters kept open for the purpose.																								 Mumbai, March 27: The government today said it will offer 6.6 per cent tax-free bonds to investors of seven assured return schemes of Unit Trust of India that have been closed before maturity. Finance secretary D. C. Gupta said the 6.6 per cent tax-free bonds are being offered from April 1.
